WEBVTT

00:15.266 --> 00:16.559
[Claire] Previously...

00:16.726 --> 00:17.518
It's her heart.

00:17.643 --> 00:18.936
-Can you fix it?
-[Claire] No, I can't.

00:19.103 --> 00:20.688
But I know somebody who can.

00:20.855 --> 00:23.190
I went through the stones once
to save my baby.

00:23.357 --> 00:26.026
We took an instant liking
to each other

00:26.193 --> 00:27.445
did we no, Adso?

00:27.611 --> 00:28.946
Hello, cat.

00:29.113 --> 00:30.948
[Jocasta] Hector had stolen
a case of gold.

00:31.115 --> 00:32.158
The king of France's mark
on it.

00:32.323 --> 00:34.118
Must be intended
for Charles Stuart.

00:34.243 --> 00:35.494
Hector.

00:35.661 --> 00:36.662
-[Jamie] News of our death.
-[Claire] January.

00:36.829 --> 00:37.997
We die in a fire.

00:38.164 --> 00:39.874
[Wendigo] Search the house.
You find anything?

00:40.040 --> 00:40.833
[Mrs. Bug] Give that gold back.

00:41.000 --> 00:43.210
[both speaking Gaelic]

00:43.335 --> 00:45.087
It's gemstones I'm after.

00:45.254 --> 00:46.338
Maybe she hid them in there.

00:46.505 --> 00:49.008
-[cabinets rattle]
-[glass shatters]

00:49.175 --> 00:50.259
What's that smell?

00:50.426 --> 00:51.969
Ether.
Don't breathe in the fumes.

00:52.094 --> 00:53.512
[thug] It's too damn dark.

00:53.679 --> 00:55.222
No! No, don't do that!

00:55.389 --> 00:56.640
[match rasps]

00:56.807 --> 00:59.727
[dramatic music plays]

01:05.316 --> 01:08.194
[spirited Celtic folk music
plays]

01:08.360 --> 01:11.322
♪ ♪

01:25.544 --> 01:28.464
[engine rumbling]

01:28.631 --> 01:31.550
♪ ♪

01:43.521 --> 01:45.356
[doorbell rings]

01:53.072 --> 01:55.574
[singer] ♪ Sing me a song ♪

01:55.699 --> 01:59.036
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

01:59.203 --> 02:01.956
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

02:02.122 --> 02:04.875
♪ Be I? ♪

02:05.042 --> 02:07.628
♪ Merry of soul ♪

02:07.795 --> 02:10.673
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

02:10.840 --> 02:13.050
♪ Over the sea ♪

02:13.217 --> 02:16.178
♪ To Skye ♪

02:16.345 --> 02:18.973
♪ Billow and breeze ♪

02:19.139 --> 02:21.725
♪ Islands and seas ♪

02:21.892 --> 02:27.565
♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪

02:27.731 --> 02:30.317
♪ All that was good ♪

02:30.484 --> 02:33.237
♪ All that was fair ♪

02:33.404 --> 02:35.573
♪ All that was me ♪

02:35.739 --> 02:38.617
♪ Is gone ♪

02:38.784 --> 02:41.078
♪ Sing me a song ♪

02:41.245 --> 02:44.248
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

02:44.415 --> 02:47.334
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

02:47.459 --> 02:49.837
♪ Be I? ♪

02:50.004 --> 02:52.298
♪ Merry of soul ♪

02:52.423 --> 02:55.466
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

02:55.593 --> 02:59.847
♪ Over the sea ♪

03:00.014 --> 03:05.936
♪ To Skye ♪

03:07.146 --> 03:09.982
[dramatic music plays]

03:10.149 --> 03:13.068
♪ ♪

03:14.904 --> 03:18.782
♪ Sing me a song ♪

03:18.949 --> 03:23.454
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

03:23.621 --> 03:28.459
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

03:28.626 --> 03:30.753
♪ Be I? ♪

03:34.632 --> 03:37.301
[children giggling]

03:43.140 --> 03:44.475
[Fiona]
We've been keeping it safe,

03:44.642 --> 03:46.477
but I've been dying to know
what's inside.

03:46.644 --> 03:48.145
The bank said
it's been in their vault

03:48.312 --> 03:49.980
for 200 years.

03:50.147 --> 03:52.983
[soft apprehensive music plays]

03:53.150 --> 03:56.111
♪ ♪

03:57.154 --> 03:59.781
Uh, maybe I should check
on the kids.

03:59.949 --> 04:02.910
They're outside in the garden
with Ernie and the girls.

04:03.077 --> 04:04.161
I'll check on them for you.

04:04.328 --> 04:05.579
Thank you.

04:05.746 --> 04:07.206
[Fiona]
I'm glad Mandy's doing so well.

04:07.373 --> 04:09.959
And so glad you've come back.

04:10.125 --> 04:11.627
[sighs]

04:16.255 --> 04:17.841
[Brianna sighs]

04:18.007 --> 04:20.928
♪ ♪

04:47.705 --> 04:49.707
[lid creaks]

04:56.755 --> 04:59.425
[Roger] Huh. A musket ball?

05:08.851 --> 05:10.019
Hmm.

05:10.185 --> 05:12.896
♪ ♪

05:20.696 --> 05:23.282
[Jamie] "My dear daughter,
as you will see

05:23.407 --> 05:25.075
"if you ever receive this,

05:25.242 --> 05:26.910
we are alive."

05:27.077 --> 05:28.162
[Claire] No! The ether!

05:28.328 --> 05:30.247
Wendigo, blow that out.

05:30.414 --> 05:33.042
[tense music plays]

05:33.207 --> 05:35.294
♪ ♪

05:35.461 --> 05:38.714
[Jamie] Arch! Murdina! Get out!

05:38.881 --> 05:40.382
Claire!

05:40.549 --> 05:43.469
♪ ♪

05:58.484 --> 06:00.778
"Both your mother and I
are safe and well.

06:00.944 --> 06:02.780
"And we will always have
a home

06:02.946 --> 06:04.865
as long as we have
each other."

06:06.617 --> 06:09.453
-[flames crackling]
-[Claire panting]

06:09.620 --> 06:12.581
♪ ♪

06:17.252 --> 06:18.879
-[Claire grunts]
-[glass shattering]

06:21.381 --> 06:22.633
-[Young Ian] Uncle!
-[Lizzie] Mistress!

06:22.800 --> 06:24.426
[Young Ian] What's happened?

06:24.593 --> 06:27.304
Run for help. We need water!

06:27.471 --> 06:30.432
♪ ♪

06:31.350 --> 06:33.185
[water splashing]

06:35.479 --> 06:36.980
Come on, men, come on!

06:42.569 --> 06:45.572
Let me. Argh!

06:51.954 --> 06:53.539
-Here.
-[Young Ian] Move back!

06:59.586 --> 07:02.506
[mournful music plays]

07:02.673 --> 07:05.551
♪ ♪

07:18.438 --> 07:20.065
[glass shatters]

07:43.672 --> 07:44.965
Enough.

07:48.177 --> 07:49.720
Enough!

07:49.845 --> 07:52.806
[flames crackling]

07:54.725 --> 07:56.101
It canna be saved.

07:58.896 --> 08:01.231
Thank you all, but...

08:01.398 --> 08:02.900
there's nothing more we can do.

08:03.066 --> 08:06.028
♪ ♪

08:13.285 --> 08:16.413
Well, it's not January.

08:16.580 --> 08:19.124
Aye.

08:19.249 --> 08:20.959
And we're no' dead.

08:22.461 --> 08:24.171
So much for our obituary.

08:24.338 --> 08:27.257
♪ ♪

08:32.554 --> 08:34.389
Bloody newspapers.

08:36.225 --> 08:38.101
Never get anything right.

08:39.352 --> 08:42.231
[fire roaring]

08:42.397 --> 08:45.317
♪ ♪

09:01.917 --> 09:03.627
You and your bloody matches.

09:06.255 --> 09:08.465
You burned the house down.

09:08.632 --> 09:10.509
[scoffs] What?

09:10.676 --> 09:13.595
No, it was Mama's ether.

09:13.762 --> 09:14.846
Come on, any kind of spark

09:15.013 --> 09:15.973
could have caused
that explosion.

09:16.139 --> 09:17.724
But it wasn't
any kind of spark.

09:17.891 --> 09:19.059
It--

09:19.226 --> 09:21.478
Wendigo lit one
of your matches.

09:21.645 --> 09:22.646
[laughing]
You and your mother...

09:22.813 --> 09:25.524
the 18th century's lucky
to have survived you.

09:25.691 --> 09:28.026
Me? Why are you saying that?

09:28.193 --> 09:30.988
[Roger]
'Cause, Brianna, it was you.

09:31.154 --> 09:34.616
You caused a fire
that they survived.

09:34.783 --> 09:37.744
A different fire.
Look at the date.

09:40.622 --> 09:43.542
The fire from the obituary
didn't happen.

09:43.667 --> 09:45.043
[chuckles] It couldn't happen.

09:45.210 --> 09:47.462
There was nothing left to burn.

09:47.587 --> 09:51.508
So we actually did it.
We saved them.

09:51.675 --> 09:53.927
We changed history.

09:57.347 --> 10:00.183
[melancholy music plays]

10:00.350 --> 10:03.270
♪ ♪

10:10.402 --> 10:12.904
[cabinet creaks]

10:39.306 --> 10:40.849
[beam thuds]

10:45.812 --> 10:48.774
[pans clanging]

10:54.071 --> 10:55.072
[trunk creaks]

10:55.238 --> 10:58.200
♪ ♪

11:23.975 --> 11:27.187
[Jamie] Your hair smells
of smoke, Sassenach.

11:27.354 --> 11:29.606
[Claire]
Everything smells of smoke.

11:35.612 --> 11:37.030
[Jamie]
When ye're called to the aid

11:37.155 --> 11:38.281
of a dying man...

11:40.242 --> 11:45.122
...why is it that
you never say no?

11:45.288 --> 11:46.206
Ever?

11:47.582 --> 11:50.085
Though you ken
the case is hopeless?

11:53.839 --> 11:55.215
Because I can't--

11:58.135 --> 11:59.469
Because I--

12:00.929 --> 12:04.683
I cannot admit
there is anything to do

12:04.850 --> 12:06.268
but go on.

12:06.435 --> 12:09.312
♪ ♪

12:16.486 --> 12:17.696
Nor will I.

12:29.458 --> 12:34.212
I'm going to go and wash
the soot out of these.

12:34.337 --> 12:37.340
♪ ♪

13:10.499 --> 13:11.666
I found this.

13:13.752 --> 13:15.212
Thought you might like it back.

13:21.051 --> 13:24.095
'Tis Willie.
Lord John's lad, no?

13:28.225 --> 13:29.184
Aye.

13:30.685 --> 13:31.937
I recognize his face

13:32.103 --> 13:34.314
from when he was here
at the Ridge.

13:35.690 --> 13:37.108
Glad to have it back. Thank ye.

13:40.695 --> 13:42.155
It's a shame
they never returned.

13:44.074 --> 13:45.033
Aye.

13:47.577 --> 13:49.204
But I did see him again.

13:51.164 --> 13:53.165
In Wilmington.

13:53.333 --> 13:55.752
Just before we saw
your cousins away.

13:57.629 --> 13:59.756
He's grown.

13:59.923 --> 14:01.132
A soldier.

14:01.299 --> 14:03.301
Goes by William now.

14:05.303 --> 14:07.639
You must be proud.

14:07.806 --> 14:10.642
[pensive music plays]

14:10.809 --> 14:13.728
♪ ♪

14:19.317 --> 14:21.486
How did you ken?

14:21.653 --> 14:25.282
When he was here,
I saw you lookin' at him

14:25.448 --> 14:27.617
the same way you were lookin'
at that portrait.

14:31.371 --> 14:35.667
That and from what I remember,
he was a stubborn lad.

14:37.127 --> 14:40.630
Wasna afraid to speak
his mind, either.

14:40.797 --> 14:42.549
Reminded me of my mother.

14:45.427 --> 14:46.553
And you.

14:52.225 --> 14:54.352
He's a Fraser sure enough.

14:57.480 --> 14:58.773
Does he ken?

15:00.317 --> 15:02.652
He can never know he's my son.

15:02.819 --> 15:06.114
[Young Ian] Dinna fash, Uncle.

15:06.239 --> 15:08.617
Ye need Fraser blood
to see it in him.

15:10.952 --> 15:12.704
I will never speak of it
to a soul.

15:12.871 --> 15:15.624
♪ ♪

15:27.969 --> 15:29.304
[horse neighs]

15:31.014 --> 15:33.308
[Lizzie] We've brought you
some parsnip soup, mistress.

15:35.852 --> 15:38.521
The fisherfolk have sent
blankets for ye.

15:38.688 --> 15:41.524
And....I-I thought
you might be needin'

15:41.691 --> 15:45.236
a spare blouse
and a shawl maybe?

15:46.446 --> 15:47.697
Lizzie...

15:47.864 --> 15:50.867
Please.
'Tis the least I can do.

15:52.202 --> 15:54.871
And if you'd like
to change now,

15:55.038 --> 15:58.208
I can help you to wash the soot
from the one you're wearin'.

16:01.044 --> 16:02.379
Thank you.

16:07.550 --> 16:09.511
Is there anything
we can help you with, mistress?

16:09.678 --> 16:12.430
Me and Kezzie could carry
what you've salvaged

16:12.555 --> 16:15.225
up to Roger and Brianna's
old cabin.

16:15.392 --> 16:16.976
That would be nice.

16:18.978 --> 16:20.689
[horse neighs]

16:24.150 --> 16:26.444
Is there something else?

16:26.611 --> 16:28.488
Adso.

16:28.655 --> 16:31.908
We looked everywhere
for your wee cheetie...

16:32.075 --> 16:35.286
in the woods, near the river,

16:35.453 --> 16:36.913
but we havena found him.

16:41.251 --> 16:43.044
I'm sure
he'll turn up somewhere.

16:44.629 --> 16:46.131
Of course he will.

16:46.297 --> 16:49.134
[mournful music plays]

16:49.300 --> 16:52.095
♪ ♪

17:05.983 --> 17:08.444
I guess you'll be wantin'
to explain this, Mr. Bug.

17:09.945 --> 17:12.531
I dinna owe ye an explanation
about anything.

17:15.160 --> 17:17.078
[Jamie] There's a mark
of the fleur-de-lis.

17:18.872 --> 17:21.750
'Twas meant for Charles Stuart
was it no'?

17:21.915 --> 17:24.042
[Arch] Aye, 'twas.

17:24.210 --> 17:25.627
And do you ken
how it came to be

17:25.795 --> 17:26.963
in your wife's possession?

17:29.174 --> 17:31.468
[thunder rumbles]

17:33.636 --> 17:35.221
Thieves burnt down my house.

17:35.388 --> 17:37.223
I willna have any more
on the Ridge.

17:37.390 --> 17:39.476
I'm no thief.

17:39.642 --> 17:41.269
Neither is my wife.

17:41.436 --> 17:44.230
It's your own blood
that's done the taking.

17:44.397 --> 17:45.857
Jocasta Cameron

17:46.024 --> 17:48.359
and that bastard
of a husband of hers, Hector,

17:48.526 --> 17:51.154
they're the thieves
you speak of.

17:51.321 --> 17:52.530
How so?

17:55.742 --> 17:56.868
There were three of us

17:57.035 --> 17:59.829
when the gold came ashore
from France.

17:59.996 --> 18:03.833
Dougal MacKenzie took one-third
and Hector Cameron another.

18:04.000 --> 18:06.419
I was the third man,
tacksman to Malcolm Grant,

18:06.544 --> 18:08.254
who sent me.

18:08.379 --> 18:11.007
[tense music plays]

18:11.174 --> 18:13.343
[Jamie] The French gold...

18:13.510 --> 18:16.679
the lost Jacobite gold...

18:16.846 --> 18:20.225
it's here in America?

18:20.391 --> 18:23.561
Aye. It is.

18:23.728 --> 18:27.023
But it came too late to make
a difference to the cause.

18:27.190 --> 18:30.735
So Grant used it
for the good of the clan.

18:30.902 --> 18:32.946
I dinna know
what Dougal did with his,

18:33.071 --> 18:36.449
but Hector Cameron, he fled.
He was a traitor.

18:36.616 --> 18:38.409
And his wife wi' him.

18:38.576 --> 18:41.538
I only had to set eyes
on River Run

18:41.704 --> 18:43.498
to see where the gold
had been spent.

18:43.665 --> 18:44.874
But not all of it.

18:46.209 --> 18:48.545
What I'm wondering...

18:48.711 --> 18:50.463
is how the devil
you found what was left of it

18:50.630 --> 18:51.756
and got it away?

18:51.923 --> 18:53.716
Each time I went to River Run,

18:53.883 --> 18:55.885
I searched
every cupboard, every closet.

18:56.052 --> 18:58.429
Then it came to me.

18:58.596 --> 19:01.182
Hector Cameron was no' a man
to part wi' anything

19:01.307 --> 19:05.353
only for reason of bein' dead.

19:05.520 --> 19:08.022
'Twas in his crypt with him.

19:08.189 --> 19:09.899
So whenever I went
to River Run,

19:10.066 --> 19:12.235
piece by piece, I took back

19:12.402 --> 19:14.821
what the coward stole
from Scotland.

19:14.946 --> 19:18.741
A man who takes from a thief
is made a thief himself.

19:18.908 --> 19:20.243
[Arch]
I only wished to take it back

19:20.410 --> 19:21.494
from the Camerons.

19:21.661 --> 19:23.997
I am a man of my word,

19:24.163 --> 19:26.583
Seaumais mac Brian.

19:26.749 --> 19:29.252
I swore an oath to my chief.

19:29.419 --> 19:31.588
And I kept it till he died.

19:31.754 --> 19:34.132
I swore an oath
to the king across the water.

19:34.299 --> 19:35.592
And I kept that too.

19:35.758 --> 19:38.261
I swore loyalty
to George of England

19:38.428 --> 19:40.096
when I came upon this shore.

19:40.221 --> 19:44.392
So tell me now,
where does my duty lie?

19:44.559 --> 19:47.520
You swore an oath to me too.

19:47.645 --> 19:49.439
I am thinking now

19:49.606 --> 19:51.649
that the oath that matters most

19:51.774 --> 19:53.776
is the one I made to my wife.

19:56.029 --> 19:58.197
Where is the rest of it?

19:58.364 --> 20:00.491
Somewhere you'll never find it.

20:07.624 --> 20:11.294
You are free
of your oath to me.

20:11.461 --> 20:12.962
Take your life from my hand.
Take this.

20:13.129 --> 20:16.132
Take your wife and go.
Do not return.

20:16.257 --> 20:19.218
♪ ♪

20:46.955 --> 20:48.873
It's all been for nothing,
Murdina.

20:49.040 --> 20:50.667
He's sending us away.

20:50.833 --> 20:51.960
What?

20:52.126 --> 20:55.004
I was chief tacksman once.
A man of worth.

20:55.171 --> 20:59.008
And in my eyes,
that's what you'll always be.

20:59.175 --> 21:01.844
There's no shame
in what we've done.

21:01.970 --> 21:04.389
I'm no' beggin' him
to let us stay here.

21:04.555 --> 21:06.557
No, sir.

21:06.724 --> 21:09.852
We've spent years on our knees

21:10.019 --> 21:13.022
scrubbin' their floors,
washin' their clothes--

21:13.189 --> 21:14.399
we've slaughtered their pigs.

21:14.565 --> 21:17.193
We've served them their meals.

21:17.318 --> 21:19.445
We've seen things

21:19.570 --> 21:21.364
and yet we look the other way.

21:23.992 --> 21:27.829
We've earned this, Archie.

21:31.332 --> 21:33.918
This is our time.

21:34.085 --> 21:36.921
[pensive music plays]

21:37.088 --> 21:40.049
♪ ♪

21:42.218 --> 21:44.762
[crickets chirping]

21:49.142 --> 21:50.893
Aye, it's him.

21:51.060 --> 21:52.895
[Young Ian] You think he hid
the gold there?

21:53.062 --> 21:54.939
He's hid it somewhere
we'd never find it

21:55.106 --> 21:56.733
right under our noses.

21:58.151 --> 22:01.320
Let him find
what he's lookin' for first.

22:01.487 --> 22:04.323
Ye go behind him.
If he runs, stop him.

22:04.449 --> 22:07.368
[tense music plays]

22:07.535 --> 22:10.413
♪ ♪

22:20.423 --> 22:21.507
[shovel thuds]

22:32.060 --> 22:33.269
Mr. Bug?

22:33.394 --> 22:35.855
Arch Bug. Come outta there.

22:36.022 --> 22:37.899
I would speak with you.

22:40.234 --> 22:41.444
[gunshot]

22:41.611 --> 22:44.447
♪ ♪

22:55.500 --> 22:56.667
Mrs. Bug?

22:58.628 --> 23:00.922
I need Arch.

23:01.089 --> 23:02.465
Archie.

23:02.632 --> 23:04.759
[gasps]

23:11.349 --> 23:13.017
[Young Ian] No.

23:13.184 --> 23:14.936
I th--thought she was...

23:15.103 --> 23:16.979
The--the coat.

23:17.146 --> 23:18.940
The hat... [gasps]

23:19.107 --> 23:21.734
[melancholy music playing]

23:21.901 --> 23:24.737
♪ ♪

23:24.904 --> 23:27.490
I...didna ken.

23:29.784 --> 23:32.120
I d--I didna ken it was you.

23:33.162 --> 23:34.205
[box thuds]

23:37.166 --> 23:38.543
[lid rattles]

23:38.709 --> 23:41.671
♪ ♪

24:08.656 --> 24:11.826
She was always kind to me.

24:14.036 --> 24:15.705
She took care of me.

24:19.333 --> 24:20.626
Of all of us.

24:24.172 --> 24:25.464
And I--

24:25.590 --> 24:28.301
And you were protecting Jamie.

24:29.552 --> 24:30.970
Aye.

24:33.014 --> 24:34.724
But she protected me.

24:37.351 --> 24:39.770
She kept our secret, Auntie.

24:41.814 --> 24:43.524
Why did I do it?

24:45.067 --> 24:49.113
The shot only grazed
Uncle Jamie.

24:51.115 --> 24:52.783
She's lyin' in there.

24:55.578 --> 24:58.539
And I canna take it back
or undo it.

25:00.750 --> 25:02.293
And yet...

25:03.753 --> 25:07.423
...I keep lookin'
for some way that I can.

25:09.425 --> 25:12.887
Somethin' I can do
to make it right.

25:13.054 --> 25:15.973
♪ ♪

25:24.482 --> 25:26.234
Are you breathing, Ian?

25:28.361 --> 25:30.821
Aye.

25:30.988 --> 25:31.948
I think so.

25:33.824 --> 25:36.077
That's all you have to do
for now.

25:43.125 --> 25:46.796
After talking to Ian,
I had to take my own advice--

25:46.963 --> 25:50.591
put on a brave face,
be strong,

25:50.716 --> 25:52.802
and keep breathing.

25:52.969 --> 25:55.930
♪ ♪

26:09.527 --> 26:10.987
Any sign of Arch?

26:11.153 --> 26:14.782
No. I called out for him after.
There was no answer.

26:14.907 --> 26:16.200
I looked around too.

26:18.577 --> 26:21.956
Why would he hide the gold
under our home?

26:22.123 --> 26:23.582
Didn't he worry
that we'd find it?

26:23.749 --> 26:25.584
[Jamie] We never did.

26:25.710 --> 26:27.169
Why did I not let her take it?

26:29.088 --> 26:30.506
What did it matter?

26:34.260 --> 26:35.594
[sighs]

26:37.388 --> 26:38.973
Murdina,

26:39.140 --> 26:41.475
wife of Archibald,

26:41.642 --> 26:43.102
you'll be missed.

26:44.729 --> 26:46.105
Amen.

26:49.191 --> 26:52.361
I hate that she's going
to her grave

26:52.528 --> 26:54.530
and things weren't right
between us.

26:54.697 --> 26:57.616
♪ ♪

27:01.203 --> 27:02.747
[Lizzie] Mrs. Bug will be
the guardian now,

27:02.913 --> 27:04.790
will she no', Mistress Fraser?

27:04.957 --> 27:06.292
It suits her.

27:06.459 --> 27:08.586
-[Claire] The guardian?
-[Jamie] Aye.

27:08.753 --> 27:10.713
The last person
to lie in a graveyard

27:10.880 --> 27:12.757
becomes its guardian.

27:12.882 --> 27:14.091
Must stand and guard

27:14.258 --> 27:17.136
until the next person dies
and comes to take their place.

27:17.303 --> 27:19.555
Only then can they rest.

27:19.722 --> 27:22.808
What is a guardian
of the graveyard guarding?

27:22.975 --> 27:24.477
And from whom?

27:24.643 --> 27:25.936
Vandals.

27:26.103 --> 27:28.230
Desecraters, charmers.

27:28.397 --> 27:30.900
Even the dead
may need defending.

27:31.067 --> 27:33.444
Who better to do that
than a ghost?

27:33.611 --> 27:37.323
I wonder
who the guardian was before.

27:37.490 --> 27:41.160
Well, if it was the last person
to be buried here...

27:43.996 --> 27:45.831
...that would be
Malva Christie.

27:47.541 --> 27:51.045
Well, Mrs. Bug
is in charge now.

27:51.212 --> 27:53.172
Malva can go home to heaven.

27:56.425 --> 27:57.468
Mr. Bug?

27:57.635 --> 27:59.762
[tense music plays]

27:59.887 --> 28:02.306
I trust you wouldna
turn an old man away

28:02.473 --> 28:04.600
from his wife's funeral.

28:04.767 --> 28:06.143
[Jamie] Of course not.

28:06.310 --> 28:08.312
I'd have her taken to her rest

28:08.479 --> 28:10.773
with the proper observances.

28:12.566 --> 28:15.569
Will you sing, Mistress Fraser?

28:17.071 --> 28:18.531
I, uh...

28:21.617 --> 28:23.119
Yes, Arch.

28:32.711 --> 28:38.676
♪ Ave Maria ♪

28:44.265 --> 28:50.187
♪ Gratia plena ♪

28:51.814 --> 28:57.695
♪ Maria gratia plena ♪

29:01.031 --> 29:03.993
♪ Maria ♪

29:04.160 --> 29:09.832
♪ Gratia plena ♪

29:09.999 --> 29:13.752
♪ Ave ♪

29:13.919 --> 29:19.383
♪ Ave Dominus ♪

29:19.550 --> 29:22.761
♪ Dominus tecum ♪

29:22.928 --> 29:25.973
[melancholy music plays]

29:26.140 --> 29:28.934
♪ ♪

29:29.101 --> 29:32.062
[Archie sobbing softly]

29:56.670 --> 30:00.007
[Jamie] "Death, be not proud...

30:01.717 --> 30:06.555
"...Though some have called
thee mighty and dreadful,

30:06.722 --> 30:08.599
"For thou art not so.

30:09.892 --> 30:12.228
"Poor Death,

30:12.394 --> 30:15.105
"one short sleep past,

30:15.272 --> 30:18.901
"we wake eternally,

30:19.068 --> 30:22.988
"and Death shall be no more.

30:23.155 --> 30:26.408
Death, thou shalt die."

30:27.785 --> 30:30.621
[crow cawing]

30:30.788 --> 30:33.749
♪ ♪

30:50.391 --> 30:51.850
Mr. Bug?

30:57.898 --> 30:59.608
It was by my hand

30:59.775 --> 31:02.861
that this woman of great worth
has died.

31:04.822 --> 31:08.033
I didna take her life by malice

31:08.200 --> 31:10.286
or-or of a purpose.

31:11.620 --> 31:13.706
And it is a sorrow to me.

31:20.629 --> 31:25.467
I swear by my iron,
a life for a life.

31:30.180 --> 31:32.850
Too easy, lad.

31:33.017 --> 31:35.936
[ominous music plays]

31:36.103 --> 31:37.354
♪ ♪

31:37.521 --> 31:39.815
Will you give me your hound
to kill?

31:42.901 --> 31:44.653
No.

31:44.778 --> 31:47.740
It was my crime, not his.

31:47.906 --> 31:49.241
Aye.

31:49.408 --> 31:50.993
You see then?

31:51.160 --> 31:54.622
He's naught
but a flea-ridden beast.

31:57.249 --> 31:58.709
Not a wife.

32:00.461 --> 32:02.671
When you've something
worth taking,

32:02.838 --> 32:04.882
you'll see me again.

32:07.468 --> 32:10.179
That I promise ye.

32:10.304 --> 32:13.223
♪ ♪

32:26.362 --> 32:28.238
[Claire]
In the days that followed,

32:28.405 --> 32:31.909
we tried to lay
our sorrows to rest.

32:32.076 --> 32:34.536
Arch Bug did not return,

32:34.703 --> 32:37.748
and so we looked towards
the future.

32:37.915 --> 32:40.751
[soft heartwarming music plays]

32:40.918 --> 32:43.879
♪ ♪

32:46.382 --> 32:48.634
This place never ceases
to amaze.

32:48.801 --> 32:49.802
Hmm.

32:52.429 --> 32:56.600
So, uh, I was thinking, maybe--

32:56.767 --> 32:58.310
you see that clearing there?

32:58.477 --> 32:59.812
[Claire] What, right over
there?

32:59.937 --> 33:00.854
[Jamie] Aye.

33:01.271 --> 33:04.817
I was thinking
maybe that will be

33:04.983 --> 33:07.444
where the new house will stand.

33:07.611 --> 33:09.363
If you think it's suitable.

33:12.366 --> 33:15.244
I didn't realize you'd
already thought of a spot.

33:15.411 --> 33:16.829
[chuckles]

33:16.995 --> 33:19.456
Started thinkin' about it
last year.

33:19.623 --> 33:22.501
Kent that if anythin'
should happen,

33:22.668 --> 33:24.837
I'd be happier
having considered

33:25.003 --> 33:26.755
what might become of us.

33:27.881 --> 33:30.217
It's good to plan ahead,
I suppose.

33:31.593 --> 33:34.805
[sighs] This is our home
no matter what.

33:40.853 --> 33:42.771
I sincerely hope

33:42.938 --> 33:44.773
I'm not the one
that has to do it.

33:44.940 --> 33:48.193
But should the question
ever arise,

33:48.360 --> 33:50.279
would you like
to be buried here

33:50.446 --> 33:52.114
or taken back to Scotland?

33:52.281 --> 33:54.450
I should be lucky
to be buried at all, Sassenach.

33:54.616 --> 33:56.744
Much more likely
I'll be drowned, burnt,

33:56.910 --> 33:58.954
or left to rot
on some battlefield.

33:59.121 --> 34:00.247
Dinna fash.

34:02.207 --> 34:04.710
If you have to dispose
of my carcass,

34:04.877 --> 34:06.503
leave it out for the crows.

34:06.670 --> 34:08.630
[chuckles softly]

34:08.797 --> 34:10.757
-I'll bear that in mind.
-Hmm.

34:15.304 --> 34:17.389
You haven't asked
what I want done with my body.

34:17.556 --> 34:20.516
No. And I never will.

34:22.060 --> 34:25.438
No, I canna think
of you dead, Claire.

34:25.606 --> 34:28.484
Anything else, but not that.

34:41.538 --> 34:43.331
When do you think
we should start building?

34:43.498 --> 34:44.583
Well, that's something

34:44.750 --> 34:46.251
I've been meanin'
to speak with you about.

34:48.253 --> 34:50.589
Keep thinkin'...

34:50.755 --> 34:52.132
about Lallybroch.

34:53.801 --> 34:56.261
You want
to go back to Scotland?

34:56.428 --> 34:58.680
Aye.

34:58.847 --> 34:59.932
Something I must do.

35:00.098 --> 35:02.893
♪ ♪

35:05.562 --> 35:08.398
I made a promise
to my sister long ago.

35:08.565 --> 35:13.070
I swore I'd bring
Young Ian back to her.

35:13.237 --> 35:15.072
This I mean to do.

35:15.239 --> 35:17.449
Although the man
I bring back to her

35:17.616 --> 35:20.828
is not the lad who left.

35:20.953 --> 35:23.080
God alone knows what
they'll make of each other.

35:23.247 --> 35:26.542
Ian and Lallybroch?

35:26.708 --> 35:29.962
God has a most peculiar
sense of humor, but...

35:30.128 --> 35:32.422
[sighs] With the war,

35:32.548 --> 35:34.508
if he is to go back,

35:34.675 --> 35:35.592
it must be now.

35:42.391 --> 35:44.810
I think that's a great idea.

35:46.061 --> 35:48.230
That's settled then.

35:48.397 --> 35:49.940
We'll leave
in a few months' time,

35:50.107 --> 35:52.568
once our affairs are in order.

35:52.734 --> 35:55.487
I'll speak with Ian
and write to Jenny.

35:58.740 --> 36:01.243
There is another reason to go,
a--

36:01.410 --> 36:03.954
another promise, ye might say.

36:04.121 --> 36:05.914
[Claire] What's that?

36:08.500 --> 36:10.961
Made a promise to myself

36:11.086 --> 36:13.422
I would never face my son

36:13.589 --> 36:15.591
across the barrel of a gun.

36:15.757 --> 36:18.677
♪ ♪

36:27.853 --> 36:30.522
God, guide me with thy wisdom.

36:30.647 --> 36:34.860
God, chastise me
with thy justice.

36:36.612 --> 36:38.614
God, help me with thy mercy.

36:40.532 --> 36:42.868
God, protect me
with thy strength.

36:45.621 --> 36:48.916
And, God, please...

36:50.876 --> 36:52.210
Let me be enough.

36:59.927 --> 37:01.803
Amen.

37:01.970 --> 37:04.806
♪ ♪

37:31.792 --> 37:33.585
[Claire sighs]

37:33.752 --> 37:36.755
Did you manage
to get some sleep?

37:36.880 --> 37:39.633
Aye. I did.

37:39.800 --> 37:41.426
Finally.

37:41.593 --> 37:44.179
[both grunt]

37:44.346 --> 37:46.890
I had another dream
of your time.

37:47.057 --> 37:49.393
[Claire] Mm-hmm? Was I in it?

37:49.559 --> 37:53.355
No. 'Twas our lassie
and the bairns.

37:56.066 --> 37:57.776
Tell me what happened.

37:59.945 --> 38:04.032
I saw them walk up
to the front door of a house.

38:04.199 --> 38:06.576
Your Roger Mac was wi' them.

38:06.743 --> 38:08.704
And they knocked and...

38:08.870 --> 38:11.623
a wee brown-haired woman
opened it.

38:11.790 --> 38:13.917
[chuckles] She laughed with joy
to see them

38:14.084 --> 38:15.377
and brought them in.

38:15.544 --> 38:18.046
They went down the hallway.

38:18.213 --> 38:20.465
And Mandy was a wee bit older.

38:20.632 --> 38:21.717
She was well.

38:26.513 --> 38:28.849
Did any of them call
this woman by name?

38:30.559 --> 38:32.227
Aye.

38:32.394 --> 38:33.979
They did.

38:37.399 --> 38:40.235
Roger Mac called her Fiona.

38:40.402 --> 38:42.946
[gasps, sighs]

38:45.615 --> 38:46.908
Were they happy?

38:48.368 --> 38:49.703
Aye.

38:51.496 --> 38:52.831
Oh, just at the last,

38:52.956 --> 38:54.875
just before I woke,

38:55.042 --> 38:56.376
wee Jem was messin' about,

38:56.543 --> 38:57.753
pickin' things up and puttin'
them down as he does.

38:57.919 --> 38:59.671
[chuckles]

38:59.838 --> 39:01.798
[Jamie] There was a thing
on-on the table.

39:01.965 --> 39:05.552
Didna ken what it was.
I'd never seen the like.

39:07.220 --> 39:11.349
It was about this wide
and just a bit longer.

39:13.351 --> 39:17.230
Something like a box, maybe,
only humped.

39:17.397 --> 39:19.399
-Humped?
-Aye.

39:19.566 --> 39:21.193
It-it had a-a thing on top

39:21.318 --> 39:22.861
like a-a wee club.

39:23.028 --> 39:24.696
Only wi' a-a knob on each end.

39:24.863 --> 39:27.824
And it was tied to the box
wi' a cord

39:27.991 --> 39:30.619
curled up on itself
like a piglet's tail.

39:30.786 --> 39:34.873
Uh, Jem reached out
to pick it up...

39:35.040 --> 39:38.418
and said,
"I wanna speak to Grandda."

39:38.585 --> 39:40.003
[Claire] It's a telephone.

39:40.170 --> 39:42.047
Telephone.

39:42.214 --> 39:44.549
You can talk to other people
through it

39:44.716 --> 39:46.635
across long distances.

39:46.802 --> 39:49.596
♪ ♪

39:51.640 --> 39:53.308
I wish we could call them.

39:57.270 --> 39:58.730
But...

40:00.690 --> 40:03.026
...our letters will have to do
for now.

40:04.945 --> 40:06.696
[sighs]

40:10.826 --> 40:12.744
[forge sizzling]

40:12.911 --> 40:15.831
♪ ♪

40:21.294 --> 40:23.421
[Jamie] This is the last
of the gold I'm gonna melt.

40:23.588 --> 40:24.923
We'll hide the rest.

40:26.466 --> 40:27.467
Now...

40:29.010 --> 40:32.305
...you willna forget
which bag to load from, aye?

40:32.472 --> 40:33.807
Dinna fash, Uncle,

40:33.974 --> 40:37.018
I promise not to use solid gold
when we're huntin'.

40:40.313 --> 40:42.899
Thinkin' what you'll say
to your ma when you see her?

40:45.235 --> 40:46.695
[sighs] Aye.

40:46.862 --> 40:49.114
Tryin' not to think too much.

40:49.281 --> 40:52.868
Get a queer feeling in my wame
when I think of Lallybroch.

40:53.034 --> 40:54.578
Why is that?

40:54.744 --> 40:57.539
Brianna told me about this book
she read in school

40:57.706 --> 41:02.210
that said once ye'd left home,
canna go back again.

41:03.295 --> 41:05.380
I think maybe 'tis true.

41:05.505 --> 41:07.424
I think you'll find
your parents

41:07.591 --> 41:10.051
much as you left them.

41:10.218 --> 41:13.597
You may come
as a greater shock to them.

41:13.763 --> 41:15.140
I'm not that much taller, am I?

41:15.307 --> 41:17.017
[both chuckle]

41:18.185 --> 41:21.229
Personally,
I prefer Robert Frost.

41:21.396 --> 41:24.524
"Home is the place where
when you have to go there,

41:24.691 --> 41:26.359
they have to take you in."

41:29.571 --> 41:31.281
No wonder you're fond
of her, Uncle.

41:31.448 --> 41:34.201
She must be
a rare comfort to you.

41:34.326 --> 41:37.412
Yeah. She keeps takin' me in.

41:37.579 --> 41:40.415
-[grunts]
-[bullets clatter]

41:40.582 --> 41:42.083
So...

41:42.250 --> 41:44.878
I suppose you must be home.
[chuckles softly]

41:45.045 --> 41:47.964
♪ ♪

41:53.511 --> 41:57.098
No one on the Ridge
kens of this gold's existence.

41:57.265 --> 41:59.100
We canna let them find out.

41:59.267 --> 42:01.603
If there's even a rumor of it,

42:01.770 --> 42:03.396
everyone here
will be in danger.

42:08.401 --> 42:09.819
How did you find this place?

42:09.986 --> 42:14.324
Uh, Jem and I came upon it
when we were huntin' one day.

42:14.491 --> 42:16.034
'Twas a secret between us.

42:16.201 --> 42:18.370
We agreed to tell no one,
not even his parents.

42:18.536 --> 42:20.288
What, nor me?

42:20.455 --> 42:22.874
A wee lad and his grandda
need at least one secret.

42:33.260 --> 42:37.847
So why do you call it
the Spaniard's Cave?

42:38.556 --> 42:40.475
On account
of the current occupant.

42:40.642 --> 42:43.520
[soft eerie music plays]

42:43.687 --> 42:44.562
♪ ♪

42:44.688 --> 42:45.814
Oh.

42:47.649 --> 42:51.319
[Jamie] We found nothin'
wi' him save his armor.

42:51.486 --> 42:53.113
And this. [grunts]

42:53.280 --> 42:56.950
♪ ♪

42:57.117 --> 42:59.995
"Nuestra Señora
de los Angeles."

43:00.161 --> 43:02.205
-Certainly Spanish.
-Aye.

43:05.250 --> 43:06.584
Was Jem scared?

43:06.751 --> 43:08.295
No.

43:08.461 --> 43:10.255
I was.

43:10.422 --> 43:12.007
We had no lantern wi' us.

43:12.173 --> 43:14.050
I almost stepped
on this fellow.

43:14.217 --> 43:15.760
[chuckles]
Thought he was alive.

43:15.927 --> 43:18.763
The shock of it was like
to stop my heart.

43:18.930 --> 43:20.849
The wee lad had a good laugh.

43:21.016 --> 43:23.184
Wonder how he came to be here.

43:23.351 --> 43:26.730
Hmm. Murdered most likely.

43:26.896 --> 43:29.316
[grunts] There's a...

43:29.482 --> 43:33.361
another wee cave over here.

43:35.822 --> 43:38.241
[Claire] Perfect place
for hiding treasure.

43:38.408 --> 43:39.451
[Jamie] Ah.

43:45.040 --> 43:46.207
[Claire]
You and Jem weren't worried

43:46.333 --> 43:48.376
about being haunted by him?

43:48.543 --> 43:50.587
No--we said the proper prayer

43:50.754 --> 43:52.714
for the repose of his soul
when I sealed the cave.

43:52.881 --> 43:54.215
[Claire chuckles softly]

43:54.382 --> 43:55.884
You really do know
the proper prayer

43:56.051 --> 43:57.218
for every occasion, don't you?

43:57.385 --> 43:59.512
[Jamie chuckles]

43:59.679 --> 44:01.765
There's always a prayer,
a nighean,

44:03.767 --> 44:05.727
even if it's only,

44:05.894 --> 44:09.356
"A Dhia, cuidich mi."

44:09.522 --> 44:11.316
-Oh, God, help me.
-[Claire chuckles softly]

44:14.027 --> 44:17.238
[pensive music playing]

44:17.405 --> 44:20.283
♪ ♪

44:22.035 --> 44:23.912
[Claire]
"Dear Bree, we've decided

44:24.079 --> 44:26.539
"to leave the Ridge
and go to Scotland.

44:26.664 --> 44:29.626
"Your father would like
to keep his word to his sister

44:29.793 --> 44:31.336
"and bring Ian home.

44:33.713 --> 44:35.090
"He fears
the forces of history

44:35.256 --> 44:37.717
"may deprive him
of a later opportunity.

44:40.303 --> 44:42.389
"But he trusts his Ardsmuir
men will take good care

44:42.555 --> 44:45.850
"of the settlers
till we return.

44:45.975 --> 44:47.227
"We've asked the Beardsleys

44:47.394 --> 44:49.771
"to look after the site
of the new house.

44:49.938 --> 44:51.773
"And I am teaching Lizzie
how to treat ailments

44:51.940 --> 44:53.775
"with herbs and medicines
in my absence.

44:53.942 --> 44:56.528
-[Lizzie] Yes.
-Chamomile.

44:58.071 --> 45:00.031
"Your father has insinuated
that I've selfishly

45:00.156 --> 45:02.492
"kept you all to myself,

45:02.617 --> 45:03.827
"so I will reluctantly
allow him

45:03.993 --> 45:06.329
"the honor of closing
this letter.

45:06.496 --> 45:09.791
Until the next time, my love."

45:09.958 --> 45:13.169
[Jamie] "My dearest daughter,
it seems strange to ask you

45:13.336 --> 45:15.296
"to pray for the safety
of a voyage

45:15.463 --> 45:16.965
"which will have been
long completed

45:17.132 --> 45:18.842
"by the time that you
learn of it,

45:19.008 --> 45:21.302
"but I ask it nonetheless.

45:22.929 --> 45:25.765
I think God takes
no account of time."

45:25.932 --> 45:28.852
♪ ♪

45:33.481 --> 45:35.316
"I wish to tell you
of the disposition

45:35.483 --> 45:36.901
"of some property

45:37.068 --> 45:40.321
"that was once held in trust
by the Camerons

45:40.488 --> 45:42.991
for an Italian gentlemen."

45:43.158 --> 45:45.660
"It is unwise to carry
all of it with us...

45:45.827 --> 45:49.539
"And therefore I've left it
in a place of safety.

45:49.706 --> 45:51.499
"Jem knows the place.

45:54.544 --> 45:57.380
"If you should at some time
have need of this property,

45:57.547 --> 45:59.340
"tell him,
'The Spaniard guards it.'

46:02.135 --> 46:04.095
He will know what it means."

46:04.721 --> 46:06.181
"If you retrieve it,

46:06.347 --> 46:09.559
"be sure to have it blessed
by a priest.

46:09.726 --> 46:11.769
There is blood upon it."

46:11.936 --> 46:13.897
So an Italian gentlemen
and the Camerons.

46:14.063 --> 46:16.691
He must mean
my Aunt Jocasta, right?

46:16.858 --> 46:18.526
And Charles Stuart maybe.

46:18.693 --> 46:21.112
He was born
and raised in Italy.

46:21.279 --> 46:23.198
Ended up dyin' in Rome.

46:23.364 --> 46:24.949
If he does mean
the Bonnie Prince,

46:25.074 --> 46:26.534
then the property...

46:28.244 --> 46:30.497
There are stories in Scotland.

46:30.663 --> 46:34.542
My people talk about
the lost Jacobite gold.

46:34.709 --> 46:36.419
Some say it was divvied up
between clans.

46:36.586 --> 46:38.463
Others say that it was buried.

46:39.923 --> 46:42.884
And if Hector Cameron took some

46:43.051 --> 46:44.969
and took it to America,

46:45.136 --> 46:46.721
I guess that would explain
how they managed

46:46.888 --> 46:48.348
to build their plantation.

46:48.515 --> 46:49.974
And Jem knows
where it's hidden?

46:50.141 --> 46:52.560
No, that's not exactly
what Da said.

46:52.727 --> 46:55.104
Yeah, you're right.

46:55.271 --> 46:58.149
Jamie would never burden anyone
with dangerous information,

46:58.316 --> 47:00.652
let alone his grandson.

47:00.777 --> 47:03.071
No, Jem likely doesn't know
anything about the gold,

47:03.238 --> 47:06.991
just about this Spaniard,
whoever that might be.

47:07.158 --> 47:10.495
He's never mentioned
anything like this to you?

47:10.662 --> 47:12.664
Mm-mm. No.

47:14.707 --> 47:16.960
We won't ask him, will we?

47:17.126 --> 47:18.545
No.

47:19.629 --> 47:23.258
But I--the-the letter says,
"If you should have need."

47:23.424 --> 47:24.425
Right.

47:24.592 --> 47:25.760
There's no need.

47:27.554 --> 47:31.474
-I am a little curious, though.
-[chuckles] Aye. Me too.

47:31.641 --> 47:34.227
This is the stuff of legend
in Scotland.

47:34.394 --> 47:36.563
But no. Our family's safe.

47:38.314 --> 47:40.525
This Spaniard, whoever he was,

47:40.692 --> 47:43.361
can keep his Jacobite gold.

47:45.405 --> 47:47.824
I mean, you know
it's supposed to be cursed.

47:47.991 --> 47:49.659
Well, then he can keep
the curse too.

47:49.826 --> 47:52.203
[chuckles]

47:52.370 --> 47:53.454
Wait, wait, wait.

47:53.580 --> 47:56.165
I-I don't want to read them
all at once.

47:57.750 --> 48:00.295
It's like once we've read them,

48:00.461 --> 48:02.547
Mama and Da will be
really gone.

48:02.672 --> 48:06.217
[solemn music plays]

48:06.384 --> 48:09.095
We'll ration 'em out
when we get back to Boston.

48:10.930 --> 48:13.224
We'll read each letter

48:13.391 --> 48:15.935
when you feel
the time is right.

48:16.102 --> 48:17.145
[Brianna] Before we leave,

48:17.312 --> 48:19.314
there's a place
I'd like you to see.

48:21.149 --> 48:22.859
[liquid pouring]

48:22.984 --> 48:26.821
[Jamie] Have you, uh,
got a penny, a nighean?

48:26.988 --> 48:29.407
Well, any sort of coin
will do.

48:29.574 --> 48:30.700
Uh...

48:35.038 --> 48:36.914
Ah.

48:37.081 --> 48:39.500
You must always give money
for a new blade

48:39.667 --> 48:41.711
so it kens you for its owner.

48:41.878 --> 48:45.423
-[Claire] Its owner?
-And it willna turn on you.

48:45.590 --> 48:49.177
Hmm. Thank you.

48:49.344 --> 48:52.388
The last one I gave you
was lost in the fire.

48:52.555 --> 48:54.557
You'll need one
for the journey.

48:54.682 --> 48:57.977
And you'll feel safer
if you have it by you.

48:58.144 --> 49:00.271
It's beautiful.

49:00.396 --> 49:03.483
Dai Jones has a-a wee smithy

49:03.650 --> 49:05.026
down near
the fisherfolk village.

49:05.193 --> 49:08.821
I had him forge
and hone the blade.

49:08.988 --> 49:10.615
Fashioned the handle myself.

49:13.743 --> 49:14.869
Fits my hand.

49:18.665 --> 49:20.708
Oh, one more thing.

49:20.875 --> 49:23.336
You must always blood a blade
so it kens its purpose.

49:23.503 --> 49:26.339
[soft heartfelt music plays]

49:26.506 --> 49:29.425
♪ ♪

49:32.220 --> 49:35.264
Blood of my blood.

49:35.431 --> 49:38.351
♪ ♪

49:52.699 --> 49:54.492
[engine rumbles]

49:54.659 --> 49:57.537
♪ ♪

50:28.776 --> 50:29.986
[chain rattles]

50:42.623 --> 50:44.542
[Brianna]
Roger, what are you doing?

50:44.709 --> 50:45.835
[Roger] Just havin' a wee look.

50:46.002 --> 50:47.086
-[pigeons cooing]
-[Brianna gasps]

50:47.253 --> 50:48.921
[Roger] Oh, Jesus.

50:49.088 --> 50:50.256
-[chuckles]
-[Brianna] Are you okay?

50:50.423 --> 50:53.384
♪ ♪

51:06.606 --> 51:09.901
[Roger] I wish I could have
seen it in its heyday.

51:10.067 --> 51:11.611
You would have loved it.

51:16.073 --> 51:18.326
[Kezzie] There we go.

51:18.493 --> 51:20.828
Oh, he's doin' it.

51:20.995 --> 51:22.330
Oh, boy.

51:22.497 --> 51:24.207
[Lizzie] This morning
he grabbed hold of my skirts

51:24.373 --> 51:26.250
and pulled himself to standin'.

51:26.417 --> 51:27.585
[Jamie] He's a braw wee lad.

51:27.752 --> 51:29.170
Just like his parents.

51:30.338 --> 51:31.672
Oh, I'm sure he'll be thrilled

51:31.839 --> 51:34.342
to have a new playmate
in the next few months.

51:34.509 --> 51:35.843
[baby coos]

51:38.763 --> 51:41.724
[Lizzie] I'm sorry, mistress.

51:41.891 --> 51:45.353
First Mr. and Mrs. MacKenzie,

51:45.520 --> 51:48.523
and now you and Mr. Fraser.

51:48.689 --> 51:50.650
That is too many goodbyes.

51:50.817 --> 51:53.027
We will come back, Lizzie.

51:53.194 --> 51:55.112
I, uh, dinna ken when exactly,

51:55.238 --> 51:56.864
but we will.

51:58.658 --> 51:59.742
[baby coos]

51:59.909 --> 52:02.370
Now, you all look after
each other.

52:06.165 --> 52:08.292
Especially you.

52:08.459 --> 52:10.002
[Kezzie] Aye, mistress.

52:10.169 --> 52:12.547
Lizzie and the bairns
will want for nothin'.

52:12.713 --> 52:14.131
-[coos]
-[sighs]

52:16.551 --> 52:18.177
[Josiah] And we'll be sure
there's skins and meat enough

52:18.344 --> 52:21.180
for anyone in the Ridge
who may find themself in need.

52:21.347 --> 52:23.057
[Jamie] Thank you, Josiah.

52:23.224 --> 52:24.934
We best get going, Sassenach.

52:25.101 --> 52:26.894
Young Ian's waitin'
with the horses.

52:27.061 --> 52:30.022
♪ ♪

52:33.651 --> 52:35.319
Bye, Lizzie.

52:35.444 --> 52:37.154
[chuckles softly]

52:37.321 --> 52:40.491
Maybe if the bairn's a girl
I'll name her Claire

52:40.658 --> 52:42.451
to keep me from missing
you too much.

52:42.577 --> 52:45.538
♪ ♪

53:16.360 --> 53:18.029
Looking for someone?

53:20.239 --> 53:21.240
Yeah.

53:22.825 --> 53:24.368
You were hoping you'd see them.

53:27.246 --> 53:29.332
I know it's silly.

53:29.457 --> 53:30.625
Definitely not silly

53:30.791 --> 53:32.919
to long for the company
of ghosts.

53:36.839 --> 53:39.175
I'm really happy we're here

53:39.342 --> 53:40.801
and that Mandy's healthy,

53:40.968 --> 53:43.888
but I can't help missing them.

53:45.848 --> 53:47.725
I want to see them too.

53:50.519 --> 53:53.481
All right, well,
I could stay here all day,

53:53.648 --> 53:56.484
but we should probably
relieve Fiona.

53:56.651 --> 53:58.319
It's almost Mandy's
witching hour.

54:03.741 --> 54:05.534
[engine rumbles]

54:06.953 --> 54:09.372
Ooh, definitely time to go.

54:12.541 --> 54:14.168
Afternoon.

54:14.335 --> 54:15.586
We were just, um...

54:16.545 --> 54:18.214
Apologies. We'll be on our way.

54:18.381 --> 54:20.049
Are you interested?

54:20.216 --> 54:21.759
Excuse me?

54:23.386 --> 54:24.428
Bloody wind.

54:25.888 --> 54:27.682
Must have knocked it down.

54:27.848 --> 54:30.810
♪ ♪

54:37.984 --> 54:39.026
[chuckles]

54:44.240 --> 54:45.866
[Rollo barks]

54:45.992 --> 54:48.995
[birds chirping]

55:00.256 --> 55:01.799
[cat mewls]

55:01.966 --> 55:03.592
[Claire] Stop! Wait!

55:03.759 --> 55:05.469
[Jamie] What is it, Sassenach?

55:05.594 --> 55:07.388
[soft meowing]

55:13.561 --> 55:15.438
-There you are.
-[cat meows]

55:15.604 --> 55:18.357
Shh, shh, shh, shh.

55:18.524 --> 55:20.234
Adso.

55:20.401 --> 55:21.986
[Adso meows]

55:22.153 --> 55:24.113
[gasps]

55:24.280 --> 55:26.323
Oh, you're all right.

55:30.536 --> 55:33.039
[sighs, sniffles]

55:35.833 --> 55:37.460
There's lots of birds
and squirrels

55:37.626 --> 55:39.253
here for you in the woods.

55:41.672 --> 55:43.924
And Lizzie'll see you
right with milk...

55:45.801 --> 55:47.678
...and a warm spot by the fire.

55:47.845 --> 55:50.765
[somber music plays]

55:50.890 --> 55:52.808
♪ ♪

55:52.975 --> 55:55.061
-[sniffles]
-[Adso meows]

55:55.227 --> 55:56.562
Go now.

55:56.729 --> 55:58.898
Go home.

55:59.065 --> 56:00.024
[meows]

56:00.191 --> 56:03.069
♪ ♪

56:12.286 --> 56:14.872
-[Claire weeps]
-I'm sorry, Claire.

56:16.207 --> 56:18.667
I'm not--[sighs]

56:18.793 --> 56:20.836
Don't worry, I'm...

56:22.963 --> 56:25.299
-It's just a cat.
-[Jamie] Aye.

56:25.466 --> 56:26.759
Aye, I know.

56:29.553 --> 56:31.305
[Clair sobs]

56:32.264 --> 56:33.516
[sniffles]

56:48.989 --> 56:50.116
[grunts]

56:54.286 --> 56:57.665
Now this will be a sign
to all who pass

56:57.832 --> 56:59.542
that they're entering
Fraser's Ridge.

56:59.708 --> 57:02.503
[heartfelt music plays]

57:02.670 --> 57:05.631
♪ ♪

57:14.390 --> 57:15.516
[sniffles]

57:20.312 --> 57:24.859
We will make it
back here one day, won't we?

57:25.025 --> 57:28.404
I never thought I'd see
bonny Scotland again.

57:28.571 --> 57:29.822
'Tis where we're bound.

57:29.947 --> 57:33.492
So...aye.

57:33.659 --> 57:35.161
We will.

57:35.327 --> 57:38.205
♪ ♪

57:48.215 --> 57:49.758
Jamie...

57:53.512 --> 57:57.892
...you will always be enough.

57:58.058 --> 58:00.978
♪ ♪

58:05.065 --> 58:06.233
[sniffles]

58:06.400 --> 58:09.320
♪ ♪
